The Morality of Having Kids in a Burning, Drowning Worldhttps://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2023/11/27/the-quickening-elizabeth-rush-book-review-the-parenthood-dilemma-gina-rushton <div>;<i>;2023-11-20T11:00:00.000Z</i>;</div>;<div>;<img src="https://media.newyorker.com/photos/6553b90693f6f09dbe74e1e1/16:9/ w_1280,c_limit/231127_r43423web-social.jpg" alt="">;</div>;<article >;<div >;</div>;<div data-attribute-verso-pattern="article-body" >;<div >;<div >;<div data-attr-viewport-monitor="" >;<button id="bookmark" aria-label="Save this story" >;<span >;<svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 22 V2.95081H14V3.93211H6V22.1845L12.5 18.5536L19 22.1845V8.83866H20V23.9508Z">;</path>;<path d="M23 3H20V0H19V3H16V4H19V7H20V4H23V3Z">;</path>;</svg>;</span>;<span >;Save this story </span>;</button>;</div>;<div data-attr-viewport-monitor="" >;<button id="bookmark" aria-label="Save this story" >;<span >;<svg width=" 24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">;<title>;Save this story</title>;<path d="M20 23.9508L12.5 19.7312L5 23.9508V2.95081H14V3.93211H6V22.1845L12.5 18.5536L19 22.1845V8.83866H20V23.9508Z">;</path>;<path d="M23 3H20V0H19V3H16V4H19V7H20V4H23V3Z">;</path>;</svg >;</span>;<span >;Save this story</span>;</button>;</div>;</div>;</div>;<div >;<div >;<div data-testid="ArticlePageChunks" >;<div >; <div >;<div data-journey-hook="client-content" data-testid="BodyWrapper">;<div >;<p >;In August, 2003, I was living in London when a weeks-long heat wave seized much of Europe, killing tens of thousands of people.停机坪在伦敦轨道高速公路上融化。葡萄牙损失了50万英亩的森林大火。多瑙河中的水位足够低，足以暴露纳粹军事遗迹 - 吉普车，一个坦克。在巴黎，抵押品是如此不知所措，以至于工人开始将尸体存放在冷藏帐篷中。 Not long before the heat finally broke, I read an apocalyptic fifty-year climate forecast in a UK newspaper while sitting on a beach in Essex. When I was finished with the article, I handed the paper to my then boyfriend and declared, “I am never having children.”我真的是这么想的。 My kids are now nine and six.</p>;<p >;This is often how it goes. There is the crystalline uncertainty of the structure and dynamics of the climate system, as limpid as an aquamarine sea: a wave is coming, even if we can't yet say how high or how fast it will be.但随后板块会在海底移动——这可能需要数年、10年或更长时间——一些模糊且无法回答的东西就会出现，就在你意识的表面之下，未知但又极其确定，以低沉而令人眼花缭乱的频率嗡嗡作响。 It's not a decision anymore. No one even asked you.</p>;<p >;Four years ago, the journalist Elizabeth Rush joined scientists aboard the research vessel Nathaniel B. Palmer, headed for Thwaites Glacier, in Antarctica.思韦茨更广为人知的名字是“末日冰川”，这是帕尔默号上的另一位记者杰夫·古德尔(Jeff Goodell)创造的，他称思韦茨为“南极洲西部冰盖其余部分的酒瓶软木塞”。思韦茨大部分位于海平面以下，温暖的海水从下面侵蚀它。 it is sloughing off billions of tons of ice each year, and scientists now estimate that an ice shelf holding the glacier back could collapse entirely within five years, accelerating Thwaites's slide into the sea.该冰川含有足够的冰，足以使全球海平面上升几英尺或更多。即便如此，帕尔默号上的研究人员还是感到震惊，在他们的观察下，在大约四十八小时的时间内，一块约二十五英里宽、延伸深度几乎是泰坦尼克号残骸深度六倍的冰架，简直就是崩塌入海。 In a report from the Palmer, for <em>;Rolling Stone</em>;, Goodell asked, “Did we just witness what amounts to a climate catastrophe playing out in real time?”</p>;<div data-testid="GenericCallout">;<div data-testid="external-link-embed--inline">;<div >;<a aria-label="&lt;strong&gt;The Best Books We Read This Week&lt;/strong&gt;" data-event-click="{&quot;element&quot;:&quot;ExternalLink&quot;,&quot;outgoingURL&quot;:&quot;https://www.newyorker.com/best-books-2023&quot;}" href="https://www.newyorker.com/best-books-2023" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">;<span >;<strong>;The Best Books We Read This Week</strong>;</span>;</a>;<p >;<em>;Read our reviews of notable new fiction and nonfiction, updated every Wednesday.</em>;</p>;</div>;<a aria-label="&lt;strong&gt;The Best Books We Read This Week&lt;/strong&gt;" data-event-click="{&quot;element&quot;:&quot;ExternalLink&quot;,&quot;outgoingURL&quot;:&quot;https://www.newyorker.com/best-books-2023&quot;}" href="https://www.newyorker.com/best-books-2023" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">;<picture >;<img alt="" src="https://media.newyorker.com/photos/63c800e4e99d89b838ada996/1:1/w_200%2Cc_limit/undefined" srcSet="https://media.newyorker.com/photos/63c800e4e99d89b838ada996/1:1/w_120,c_limit/undefined 120w" sizes="100vw"/>;</picture>;</a>;</div>;</div>;<p >;Antarctica is nature's egg timer, poised to tell us when we're fully cooked.但是，对于拉什来说，大陆提出了另一种阈值，这是个人转型的序言。她写道：“我去南极洲的Thwaites冰川也是我决定试图在身体内部发展人的那一年。” 。 The title carries a double meaning: “quickening” refers both to the moment when a pregnant woman first feels her baby stirring inside her and to the terrifying acceleration of climate change that is especially palpable in Antarctica. “加快”的核心悖论是建立人类生命与即将毁灭的亲密关系的私人冲动。拉什写道：“如果我生一个孩子，他们的温室气体排放将导致每年还活着的大约五十平方米的海冰融化。” “Just by existing, they will make the world a little less livable for everyone, themselves included.”</p>;<p >;Rush was a Pulitzer finalist for her previous book, “Rising: Dispatches from the New American Shore,” which focussed on the kinds of low-lying coastal communities that would be decimated by the collapse of Thwaites.她的专业知识意味着她对气候变化带来的威胁没有任何幻想，但是她对父母身份的渴望揭示了这种幻想的有用性。她鼓励自己，并延伸她的读者，将南极“不是在地球底部成为一个荒凉的岛屿，而是作为母亲，这是一个足够强大的人，足以将新生活带入世界。” She draws an implicit parallel between putting off having children and humankind's delayed reckoning with climate change.她写道：“一次，我似乎已经发现自己几乎坐在东西的极限上，想知道我必须采取多长时间的行动。” She juxtaposes the “shattering” of Thwaites and the bodily wreckage of childbirth.</p>;<div>;<div role="presentation" aria-hidden="true">;<div >;</div>;<div >;</div>;</div>;</div>;<p >;In forging, Shackleton-like, toward new frontiers of the pathetic fallacy, Rush is seeking signs of hope and optimism in our climate future—or, at the very least, grasping for ambiguity, equivocation, room to negotiate on the question of how utterly fucked we all are.她发现自己在气候科学中而是在语言本身中寻找的东西。扫描了脚下稀疏的稀疏铺路时，她读到符文时，符文带有人文主义的koans和孕妇隐喻。如果您也召集了一个孩子进入人类世的MAW，那么很容易同情这种神奇的思维（视为命运）。但是，在帕尔默（Palmer）上的地图表上方录制的便条可能会发出警告，以警告诗意使南极洲的诗意：“永远不要忘记：冰告诉你该怎么做，而不是你告诉冰做什么。”冰是一个独裁的父母，对我们对她的想法或想要的东西都不动。 If Antarctica is your mother, you will not be raised well.</p>;<p >;“Having a child is at once the most intimate, irrational thing a person can do, prompted by desires so deep we hardly know where to look for their wellsprings, and an unavoidably political act,” Meehan Crist wrote in the <em>;London Review of Books</em>;, in 2020. That essay, “Is It OK to Have a Child?”—the title paraphrases a question posed by Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, the congresswoman from New York, in an Instagram live stream—is the lodestar of a growing body of commentary that debates the morality and ethics of procreation in this burning, drowning world. “似乎越来越清楚，”克里斯特继续说道，“我们生活在一个地球生命急剧不稳定的时代，这使得生育孩子的行为变得更加复杂，而社会尚未解决这一问题。”活动人士也试图对当下做出同样激进的反应。 The women of the short-lived BirthStrike movement, which garnered attention at the end of the twenty-tens, renounced having children on account of the ecological emergency, although their message was often misconstrued as a Malthusian appeal for population control.</p>;<p >;It's unclear, all in all, precisely how much correlation exists between rising awareness of the environmental crisis and steady declines in the US birth rate, which dropped for six consecutive years through 2020, reaching a historic low. It had a post-<em >;COVID</em>; bump in 2021, but stayed flat in 2022. Some of the slide can be attributed to fewer unintended and teen-age pregnancies—although the Supreme Court's ruling last year in Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization, overturning the constitutional right to abortion, may reverse those trends. (The freedom to hem and haw over having kids is a recent development in human history, and not a dilemma faced by those who currently lack reproductive rights.)</p>;<div data-attr-viewport-monitor="inline-recirc " >;</div>;<p >;In a 2021 Pew survey of childless adults who say they likely will not have children, only five per cent specifically named climate change as the crucial factor, with an additional nine per cent citing “the state of世界。”十九％的人引用了医疗原因，有17％引用了财务原因，而有15％的人引用了没有合伙人的原因。 That being said, among people who already have kids, more than half say that climate anxiety does influence how many children they plan to have, according to a Morning Consult poll of thousands of parents in five countries, including the US, conducted earlier this year.</p>;<p >;In “The Parenthood Dilemma: Procreation in the Age of Uncertainty,” (Astra), Gina Rushton portrays her own ambivalence toward becoming a mother—and the ambivalence among millennial and Gen Z women more generally—as the result of a complex and extremely familiar interplay of factors.这些不仅包括气候焦虑，还包括财务限制，工作和职业的需求，健康风险（以及与之息息相关的种族差异），性别歧视（以及使其复杂化的种族主义）以及持续的失衡异性恋伙伴关系中的家庭和情感劳动。 Rushton是澳大利亚生殖健康的作家，他决心保持无子女。然后，有一天，她发现自己在急诊室，腹部疼痛的痛苦中，签署了同意书，以允许医生去除她的一个卵巢。 “I don't want kids, you know I don't want kids,” Rushton kept telling her boyfriend and her mother, and yet she was saddened and panicked by the prospect of her fertility being compromised. (In the end, the ovary was saved.) She felt free in her choice until, all at once, it no longer seemed hers to make.</p>;<figure >;<div >;<span >;<div data-attr-viewport-monitor="" >;<a data-event-click="{&quot;element&quot;:&quot;ExternalLink&quot;,&quot;outgoingURL&quot;:&quot;https://www.newyorker.com/cartoon/a28248&quot;}" href="https://www.newyorker.com/cartoon/a28248" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">;<picture >;<img alt="Couple in kitchen reading cooking instructions on package." src="https://media.newyorker.com/cartoons/6553cb846086f3c3f4a2d7fe/master/w_1600%2Cc_limit/231127_a28248.jpg" srcSet="https://media.newyorker.com/cartoons/6553cb846086f3c3f4a2d7fe/master/w_120,c_limit/231127_a28248.jpg 120w, https://media.newyorker.com/cartoons/6553cb846086f3c3f4a2d7fe/master/w_240,c_limit/231127_a28248.jpg 240w, https://media.newyorker.com/cartoons/6553cb846086f3c3f4a2d7fe/master/w_320,c_limit/231127_a28248.jpg 320w, https://media.newyorker.com/cartoons/6553cb846086f3c3f4a2d7fe/master/w_640